## Styling — NativeWind v5 + shared tokens

The mobile app styles with **NativeWind v5 (preview)**, which compiles
Tailwind classes into React Native style objects.

### Design tokens

`apps/mobile/global.css` defines CSS custom properties that mirror the
web app's "Warm Industrial" palette (`--background`, `--primary`,
`--foreground`, etc.) plus a `@theme inline` block that maps them into
`--color-*` utility names.

`apps/mobile/tailwind.config.js` extends the shared preset
(`@sous/config/tailwind-preset`), so the same semantic utility names
work on both platforms:

```tsx
<View className="bg-card border border-border rounded-md p-4">
  <Text className="text-foreground font-sans">Hello</Text>
</View>
```

### Rules

1. **Use semantic classes** — `bg-primary`, `text-foreground`, etc.
   Never hardcode hex values in `style={{…}}` unless the property isn't
   available as a token (e.g. rare overlay `rgba(0,0,0,0.25)` — see
   `AuthGate`'s spinner overlay for the one place this is OK).
2. **Dark mode follows the system** via `useColorScheme()` and
   `ThemeProvider` in `app/_layout.tsx`. Use `dark:` variants if you
   need to override in one direction.
3. **Prefer the shared `components/ui/text.tsx` `StyledText`** for text
   — it already binds the design tokens to RN `Text` correctly. Raw
   `<Text>` with `className="text-foreground"` works too but is less
   consistent with the rest of the app.
4. **Do not add `expo-symbols` icons to web**. The app bundle for
   `expo start --web` uses `hooks/use-color-scheme.web.ts` — keep
   platform-specific files in sync.

